I went to this restaurant for an early dinner with my boss and coworker a couple of weeks ago.
We arrived around 4pm and the place was empty which wasn't surprising given the time of day.
My first impression was that the place is chic and upscale or typical Scottsdale and I don't mean that as an insult.
We started out with the Bruschetta Caprese appetizer and drinks.
I'm not a fan of caprese items so I won't comment on the appetizer other than to say the boss and co-worker liked it.
When I asked for a beer list, I was told they didn't have one.
So I asked for a rundown of what was on tap and in bottle.
Our waiter's accent was so thick that I couldn't understand a single name besides Fat Tire (by New Belgium) in a bottle.
I ordered that because after all, I couldn't understand any of the other options so I went with what I knew.
I found it disappointing that an upscale establishment like this wouldn't have something less generic that Fat Tire to offer to beer drinkers.
Tommy V's isn't that far from three local breweries (Papago, Four Peaks, and San Tan) so why go with something as bland (my opinion) as Fat Tire as your only craft beer?
I think someone needs to introduce Tommy V's managers to the idea of "Drink Local".
For dinner, I ordered the recommended Grilled Cheese and Short Rib Sandwich (Arugula, Pickled Caramelized Onion, Manchego & Cheddar Cheese) with fries.
The meat in the sandwich was tasty as was the cheese, but the bread was a soggy mess with grease.
I wouldn't order it again, but if you don't mind the mess and like short ribs, you'll probably like this meal.
For dessert, we got the cannolis.
I don't have a lot of experience with cannolis (I prefer other Italian treats like tiramisu), but my coworker said they were too sweet.
I thought the pastry part was delicious - nice and crisp and the filling was very sweet, but eaten slowly, it was a nice combination.
There are a couple of things on their menu that I want to try someday, but wasn't hungry enough to order at this visit so I'll be going back.

